<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-725-732  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 725 732.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 6 1990 v7 n30 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lighter side. (Maricopa Technical Community College developsVAX-based program to identify potential high school dropouts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vizard, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Maricopa Technical Community CollegeColleges and UniversitiesSecondary SchoolsCustom SoftwareData AnalysisProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>LIGHTER SIDEandM;Believing that a stitch in time saves nine, Maricopa Technical CommunityCollege of Phoenix, Ariz., has developed a VAX-based program that makes useof a natural language front-end tool to identify high school students who are&quot;at risk&quot; of dropping out of school.andM;Data about local high school students is stored in an Ingres database on theVAX at the college, and accessed remotely by high school faculty usingstandard English commands that are converted to SQL commands by a front-enddatabase tool from Natural Language.andM;All this appears to be having a positive effect, with 25 of the 27 &quot;at risk&quot;students identified last year graduating.andP;  But one can't help wonder aboutwhat happened to the days when &quot;at risk&quot; students were more commonly known asmalcontents, delinquents or just simple boneheads, and the principal knewevery one of them by name, and their misdeeds by heart.andM;In a world gone wild for high tech, it would seem we're now well on our wayto updating one of our more timeless expressions to &quot;Spare the VAX, spoil thechild.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>